    <script>
        const nodeData = {
            // Gateway Arguments
            funding: {
                title: "How do we pay for it?",
                content: `
                    <h3>Gateway: Funding Question</h3>
                    <p>This question immediately reveals household budget thinking. Regardless of your initial response about monetary sovereignty, critics will pivot to:</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Typical Pivot Sequence:</strong><br>
                        1. "But what about bond markets?" → Inflation concerns<br>
                        2. "This will cause inflation" → Historical examples<br>
                        3. "Look at Venezuela/Zimbabwe" → Institutional differences<br>
                        4. Eventually: Definitional disagreement about what "funding" means
                    </div>
                    <p>The initial framing doesn't matter—all funding questions converge on the same core concerns about inflation, constraints, and monetary operations.</p>
                `
            },
            inflation: {
                title: "Won't this cause inflation?",
                content: `
                    <h3>Gateway: Inflation Fears</h3>
                    <p>The most direct route to core MMT debates. Even successful rebuttals about resource constraints trigger predictable pivots:</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Inevitable Progression:</strong><br>
                        1. Quantity theory → Resource constraint response<br>
                        2. "What about expectations?" → Institutional credibility<br>
                        3. "Political discipline needed" → Japan/historical examples<br>
                        4. Circular loop through same evidence interpretations
                    </div>
                    <p>This gateway fastest reaches the core recursive patterns.</p>
                `
            },
            debt: {
                title: "What about the debt?",
                content: `
                    <h3>Gateway: Debt Sustainability</h3>
                    <p>Debt questions always pivot through the same sequence regardless of sectoral balance explanations:</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Standard Progression:</strong><br>
                        1. Sectoral balance explanation → "But interest payments?"<br>
                        2. Central bank can set rates → "What about markets?"<br>
                        3. Operational sovereignty → "International constraints?"<br>
                        4. Import dependency → Back to inflation concerns
                    </div>
                    <p>All debt arguments eventually become inflation or institutional constraint arguments.</p>
                `
            },
            printing: {
                title: "Just printing money?",
                content: `
                    <h3>Gateway: Money Creation</h3>
                    <p>Operational questions about money creation follow predictable patterns:</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Typical Flow:</strong><br>
                        1. Bank lending analogy → "But that's productive"<br>
                        2. Government spending value → "Markets more efficient"<br>
                        3. Market failure examples → "But institutional capture"<br>
                        4. Democratic accountability → Political feasibility concerns
                    </div>
                    <p>Even technical discussions about monetary operations end up as ideological disagreements about government versus market roles.</p>
                `
            },
            // Pivot Points
            "inflation-pivot": {
                title: "The Inflation Pivot",
                content: `
                    <h3>Universal Pivot: Inflation Concerns</h3>
                    <p><strong>Every MMT argument eventually pivots to inflation.</strong> Whether you start with funding, debt, or operations, critics consistently shift to inflation fears when other objections fail.</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Why This Pivot Always Happens:</strong><br>
                        • Most emotionally resonant concern for audiences<br>
                        • Allows invocation of historical "proof" (Zimbabwe, etc.)<br>
                        • Shifts from technical to visceral arguments<br>
                        • Creates opening for expectations/confidence discussions
                    </div>
                    <p>Recognizing this inevitable pivot allows strategic preparation rather than reactive responses.</p>
                `
            },
            "institutional-pivot": {
                title: "The Institutional Pivot",
                content: `
                    <h3>Universal Pivot: Institutional Constraints</h3>
                    <p>When technical MMT explanations succeed, critics pivot to institutional limitations: legal restrictions, political feasibility, democratic constraints.</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>The Constraint Cascade:</strong><br>
                        1. "Laws prevent this" → Laws can be changed<br>
                        2. "Politicians can't be trusted" → Democratic design questions<br>
                        3. "Voters won't support it" → Education and communication<br>
                        4. "International pressure" → Sovereignty trade-offs
                    </div>
                    <p>This pivot reveals that objections aren't really about MMT's technical validity but about institutional design preferences.</p>
                `
            },
            "empirical-pivot": {
                title: "The Historical Evidence Pivot",
                content: `
                    <h3>Universal Pivot: Historical Examples</h3>
                    <p>All MMT debates eventually invoke the same historical cases, regardless of initial topic. Japan, Venezuela, Zimbabwe become recurring battlegrounds.</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>The Evidence Loop:</strong><br>
                        • Japan: MMT vindication vs. stagnation concerns<br>
                        • Venezuela/Zimbabwe: Supply collapse vs. money printing<br>
                        • Weimar: Political chaos vs. monetary expansion<br>
                        • Each side claims historical vindication
                    </div>
                    <p>These examples recur because they're the few clear cases where monetary and fiscal policy intersected with extreme outcomes—but interpretation depends on theoretical framework.</p>
                `
            },
            "definitional-pivot": {
                title: "The Definitional Pivot",
                content: `
                    <h3>Universal Pivot: What Words Mean</h3>
                    <p>MMT debates consistently reach points where participants realize they're using key terms differently: "money," "debt," "funding," "borrowing," "printing."</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Common Definitional Conflicts:</strong><br>
                        • "Funding": Finding existing money vs. creating new money<br>
                        • "Borrowing": Market constraint vs. operational choice<br>
                        • "Debt": Burden vs. asset<br>
                        • "Printing": Physical currency vs. digital creation
                    </div>
                    <p>This pivot often ends debates because resolving requires accepting different foundational frameworks rather than just better arguments.</p>
                `
            },
            // Loops
            "inflation-loop": {
                title: "The Inflation-Employment Loop",
                content: `
                    <h3>Recursive Loop: Inflation vs Employment</h3>
                    <p>This loop cycles through the same arguments repeatedly:</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>The Cycle:</strong><br>
                        1. "MMT ignores inflation" → NAIRU critique<br>
                        2. "Job Guarantee manages inflation" → Make-work criticism<br>
                        3. "Unemployment is costly" → Inflation expectations<br>
                        4. "Expectations manageable" → Back to NAIRU<br>
                        <em>Repeat indefinitely...</em>
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Why it's recursive:</strong> Reflects fundamental disagreement about inflation-unemployment trade-offs that can't be resolved through better arguments alone.</p>
                `
            },
            "consolidation-loop": {
                title: "Treasury-Central Bank Loop",
                content: `
                    <h3>Recursive Loop: Institutional Separation</h3>
                    <p>Debates about treasury-central bank coordination become circular:</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>The Cycle:</strong><br>
                        1. "Treasury and Fed must be separate" → Operational reality<br>
                        2. "They already coordinate" → Legal independence<br>
                        3. "Laws can change" → Democratic accountability<br>
                        4. "Accountability requires separation" → Back to independence<br>
                        <em>Loop continues...</em>
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Why it's recursive:</strong> Mixing descriptive claims about current operations with normative claims about institutional design creates logical circularity.</p>
                `
            },
            "japan-loop": {
                title: "The Japan Evidence Loop",
                content: `
                    <h3>Recursive Loop: Japanese Case Study</h3>
                    <p>Japan becomes a recurring battleground with circular interpretations:</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>The Cycle:</strong><br>
                        1. "Japan proves fiscal space exists" → Stagnation response<br>
                        2. "Stagnation shows MMT limits" → Demographics explanation<br>
                        3. "Demographics not fiscal constraint" → Japanese government denial<br>
                        4. "Officials don't understand operations" → Back to evidence<br>
                        <em>Interpretations loop...</em>
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Why it's recursive:</strong> Same evidence interpreted through different theoretical lenses yields opposite conclusions.</p>
                `
            },
            // Terminal Points
            definitional: {
                title: "Definitional Impasse",
                content: `
                    <h3>Terminal Point: Different Definitions</h3>
                    <p>Debates end when participants realize fundamental terms mean different things in their respective frameworks.</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Common Recognition:</strong><br>
                        "We're talking past each other because we define [money/debt/funding] differently."
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Strategic Response:</strong> Acknowledge definitional differences early and focus on operational realities rather than theoretical consistency.</p>
                `
            },
            empirical: {
                title: "Empirical Standoff",
                content: `
                    <h3>Terminal Point: Historical Evidence Impasse</h3>
                    <p>Debates end when both sides realize they interpret the same historical evidence differently.</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Common Recognition:</strong><br>
                        "We both see Japan/Venezuela differently. History doesn't resolve this."
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Strategic Response:</strong> Focus on current UK context rather than international comparisons. Emphasize institutional quality and specific circumstances.</p>
                `
            },
            values: {
                title: "Value Disagreement",
                content: `
                    <h3>Terminal Point: Different Values</h3>
                    <p>Debates end when economic arguments reveal underlying disagreements about government's proper role in society.</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Common Recognition:</strong><br>
                        "This isn't really about economics—it's about what kind of society we want."
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Strategic Response:</strong> Acknowledge value differences and focus on shared goals (employment, stability) rather than governmental mechanisms.</p>
                `
            },
            complexity: {
                title: "Complexity Fatigue",
                content: `
                    <h3>Terminal Point: Technical Overwhelm</h3>
                    <p>Debates end when technical details become too complex for participants to process effectively.</p>
                    <div class="popup-example">
                        <strong>Common Recognition:</strong><br>
                        "This is getting too complicated. We need experts to sort this out."
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Strategic Response:</strong> Return to simple principles and practical outcomes. Avoid technical rabbit holes in public discussions.</p>
                `
            }
        };

        function showPopup(id) {
            const data = nodeData[id];
            if (data) {
                document.getElementById('popup-content').innerHTML = data.content;
                document.getElementById('popup-overlay').style.display = 'block';
                document.getElementById('details-popup').style.display = 'block';
            }
        }

        function hidePopup() {
            document.getElementById('popup-overlay').style.display = 'none';
            document.getElementById('details-popup').style.display = 'none';
        }

        // Event listeners
        document.querySelectorAll('.node').forEach(node => {
            node.addEventListener('click', () => {
                const id = node.getAttribute('data-id');
                showPopup(id);
            });
        });

        document.getElementById('close-btn').addEventListener('click', hidePopup);
        document.getElementById('popup-overlay').addEventListener('click', hidePopup);

        // Keyboard support
        document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
            if (e.key === 'Escape') {
                hidePopup();
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
